# Complete Implementation of Send, Receive, and Enqueue Methods

## Send Methods

```csharp
public void Send(Message message)
{
    _logger.QueueSend(message.Id);
    try
    {
        Store.StoreOutgoing(message);
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        _logger.QueueSendError(message.Id, ex);
    }
}

public void Send(params Message[] messages)
{
    _logger.QueueSendBatch(messages.Length);
    try
    {
        Store.StoreOutgoing(messages.AsSpan());
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        _logger.QueueOutgoingError(ex);
    }
}
```

**Key characteristics:** Both overloads persist messages to outgoing storage synchronously without blocking. They handle single messages or batches through the message store interface.

## Enqueue Method

```csharp
public void Enqueue(Message message)
{
    _logger.QueueEnqueue(message.Id, message.QueueString);
    Store.StoreIncoming(message);
}
```

**Key characteristics:** This method "adds a message directly to a local queue without sending it over the network," storing it for immediate availability.

## Receive Method

```csharp
public async IAsyncEnumerable<MessageContext> Receive(
    string queueName, 
    int pollIntervalInMilliseconds = 200, 
    [System.Runtime.CompilerServices.EnumeratorCancellation] CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
```

This async iterator returns a stream that polls persisted messages from storage, yielding each as a `MessageContext` object. It respects cancellation tokens and implements polling delays when no messages exist.

**No separate I/O methods exist**—operations delegate directly to the `IMessageStore` interface for actual persistence.
